{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fe16dc77-c059-4dc5-8547-776e54957852","content":"In .NET MAUI, `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` **still exist** on the `Application` class and work as before. However, the preferred approach is now **`Window` lifecycle events**, which give you finer-grained control:\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI Window equivalent |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `Created` / `Activated` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `Deactivated` / `Backgrounding` / `Stopped` |\n| `OnResume()` | `Resumed` / `Activated` |\n\nOverride `CreateWindow` in your `App` class:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\nFor **platform-specific** lifecycle hooks, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android.OnStop(activity => { /* ... */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios.WillTerminate(app => { /* ... */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**TL;DR**: Your existing overrides still compile and run, but migrating to `Window` events is recommended for multi-window support and platform parity.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a2450e84-cf8e-4be9-be43-609b4ddf28df","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` in your `Application` subclass.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`. Specifically:\n\n- The `Application` class still exists but the preferred approach is using the `Window` lifecycle events.\n\n\n- Actually, the `Application` class still supports `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` directly, so those methods haven't been removed. However, the recommended pattern has shifted toward `Window` lifecycle events, which you can access by overriding `CreateWindow()` or configuring lifecycle events through `ConfigureLifecycleEvents()`.","outputTokens":843,"requestId":"9BCD:1FFE72:62ABCAB:6DDB230:69EC0EF4"},"id":"b7e6704d-ca8f-4e1b-bd57-3ad5afa6c71e","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:46:59.303Z","parentId":"5990ddf3-7540-4759-b380-73735ff552b2"}
